<TEXTAREA NAME="ReplyMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">[QUOTE]Originally posted by Arhu:
[I]First, thank you very much once more for giving us more insight on what "Project C" (hope the trademark thingy will be solved soon - I'm itching to know the real name) will be like.

Then I try to answer to your question (hard one, you know..)

The [i]player's character[/i] should of course be able to find his way on his own. So if you click on a position in the game world with many obstacles lying around, he should avoid them. In BG, for example this was not always done well: here a river, there a bridge, and the party taking a nap while they ought to go to the other side. [i]If[/i] there really was no way to reach a place, the character should mention this fact or give other intelligent suggestions on what to do or reasons for him not being able to go there - rather than just stop walking. (These statements should, however, not always be the same, like: Click - "no, I can't get there." Click - "no, I can't get there." Click...)

But while the main character is generally just as intelligent in performing his action as his master (i.e. player), the other beings are not. They should be able to [i]do mainly the same things, the player can do.[/i]
Say, the player can move objects like a chair, throw wood into a fire-place to make it get warmer (e.g. cause he caught a cold while he swam in a river although it was raining / snowing), hop around if he wants to, open chests, talk to other people, etc.
So why can't other people do the same?

For [i]enemies[/i] the same thing applies. He should not just fire spells on the character and shot arrows at him. The more intelligent opponent could run away if he has to regenerate, or hide and attack, or hire other ones to help him, etc. (Of course it wouldn't be very funny to run after each creature that is too scared.)
Bowmen could fire where the character will be in a moment, if he stays running in a specific direction..

Well, err.. now I've somehow lost track on what I wanted to to say (I'm tired you know), so to put it in a nutshell:
All the player can do - others can do, or more.

[i]Meow...[/i]
Arhu, yawning

[This message has been edited by Arhu (edited 15-11-1999).][/I][/QUOTE]

</TEXTAREA>
